      <h2 class='article'>
        <a name="porcelain"></a>
        Porcelain
        <a href='/word_detail.php?id=23686' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'cíqì', 'chinaware / porcelain')" 
        onmouseout='hideToolTip()'>瓷器</a>
      </h2>
      <h3 class='article'>
        <a name="background"></a>
        Background
        <a href='/word_detail.php?id=1826' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'bèijǐng', 'background')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">背景</a>
      </h3>
      <p>
        The term ceramics <a href='/word_detail.php?id=25475' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'táocí qì', 'ceramics')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">陶瓷器</a> includes pottery <a href='/word_detail.php?id=22975' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'táoqì', 'pottery')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">陶器</a>, terracotta <a href='/word_detail.php?id=25205' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'chìtáo', 'terracotta')" 
        onmouseout='hideToolTip()'>赤陶</a>, and porcelain <a href='/word_detail.php?id=23686' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'cíqì', 'chinaware / porcelain')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">瓷器</a>.
        Porcelain differs from the pottery that it evolved from in the firing temperatures and vitrification (transformation 
        into glass) of the clay.
        Porcelain needs to be fired at a temperature of at least 1,200°C, use clay with at least 2% iron,
        and have an even application of glaze.
      </p>
      <p>
        Porcelain originated in China and is one of China's great contributions to the world.
        Porcelain artifacts from China have been highly prized around the world for the last two thousand years.
        Chinese porcelain is immediately impressive to look at but most people probably would not guess the depth and 
        breadth of the technology and artistic talent behind it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Porcelain was produced at centers, actually factories, where expertise and facilities were concentrated.
        The term <span class='bookTitle'>kiln</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=11465' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '窯 yáo', 'kiln / oven')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">窑</a> expanded in meaning from an oven for firing pottery to include the entire porcelain factory.
        A type of kiln called the <span class='bookTitle'>dragon kiln</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=25741' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '龍窯 lóngyáo', 'dragon kiln')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">龙窑</a> appeared in the Warring States period that could reach high temperatures.
        The first kiln of this type was in the city of Zeng in Guangdong.
        Later, another kiln was built at Shanglu in Zhejiang in the Eastern Han.
        The kiln type is long compared to its width and uses rising heat from a heating chamber at its base.
        There is a smoke vent at the top, which can be blocked to obtain a reducing atmosphere.
        By the Eastern Han it could achieve the temperature of 1,200 degrees Celsius needed for firing porcelain.
        Other types of kilns were developed later.
        A replica of the <span class='bookTitle'>egg-shaped kiln</span> used at Jingdezhen in the Qing is shown below.
      </p>
      <div class="picture">
        <a href='illustrations_use.php?mediumResolution=jingdezhen_kiln400.jpg'><img class='use' src='images/jingdezhen_kiln400.jpg' alt='egg-shaped kiln' title='egg-shaped kiln'/></a>
        <div>
          <div class='picture_header'><a href='/word_detail.php?id=17023' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '景德鎮 Jǐngdézhèn', 'Jingdezhen')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">景德镇</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=25742' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '蛋形窯 dàn xíng yáo', 'egg-shaped kiln')" 
          onmouseout="hideToolTip()">蛋形窑</a></div>
          <a href='/word_detail.php?id=3355' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'qīng', 'clear / distinct / complete / pure')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">清</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=8544' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Dào Guāng', 'Dao Guang / Emperor Dao Guang')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">道光</a>（1821〜1850<a href='/word_detail.php?id=438' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'nián', 'year')" 
          onmouseout="hideToolTip()">年</a>） <a href='/word_detail.php?id=1559' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Shànghǎi', 'Shanghai')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">上海</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=3974' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '博物館 bówù​guǎn', 'Museum')" 
          onmouseout="hideToolTip()">博物馆</a>
          <div class='picture_header'>Jingdezhen egg-shaped kiln (replica)</div>
          Shanghai Museum
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        Well known early kilns in the Tang included the <span class='bookTitle'>Yue Kiln</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=25597' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Yuè Yáo', 'Yue Kiln')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">越窑</a> near present day Shaoxing in Zhejiang province and the
        <span class='bookTitle'>Wuzhou Kiln</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=25600' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Wùzhōu Yáo', 'Wuzhou Kiln')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">婺州窑</a>  near Jinhua, also in Zhejiang.
        The Yue Kiln well-known for producing <span class='bookTitle'>celedon</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=25598' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'qīngcí', 'celadon')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">青瓷</a>, a green colored variety of porcelain.
        In the Song Dynasty porcelain reached a peak with kilns being set up all over China, each one having its own unique style. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Perhaps the most famous is the imperial <span class='bookTitle'>Jingdezhen Kiln</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=17023' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '景德鎮 Jǐngdézhèn', 'Jingdezhen')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">景德镇</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=11465' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '窯 yáo', 'kiln / oven')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">窑</a> in present day Jiangxi province, which is still a major center for porcelain today.
        A picture of the <span class='bookTitle'>Jingdezhen Kiln</span> imperial porcelain factory is shown above.
        The well known <span class='bookTitle'>blue and white porcelain</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=25581' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'qīnghuā', 'blue and white porcelain')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">青花</a> was developed at Jingdezhan in the Yuan Dynasty.
        The clay used at Jingdezhen is taken from a nearby hill called <span class='bookTitle'>Gaoling</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=26485' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '高嶺 Gāolǐng', 'Gaoling / Kaolin')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">高岭</a>, which is the orgin of the English word
        Kaolin, a common type of clay with a white color.
        One of the best known kilns in Northern China is the civilian <span class='bookTitle'>Cizhou Kiln</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=25604' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '磁州窯 Cízhōu Yáo', 'Cizhou Kiln')" 
        onmouseout='hideToolTip()'>磁州窑</a>, located in present day Hebei province.
      </p>
      <div class="picture">
        <a href='illustrations_use.php?mediumResolution=jingdezhen_400.jpg'><img class='use' src='images/jingdezhen_400.jpg' alt='Jingdezhen' title='Jingdezhen'/></a>
        <div>
          <div class='picture_header'><a href='/word_detail.php?id=17023' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '景德鎮 Jǐngdézhèn', 'Jingdezhen')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">景德镇</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=11465' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '窯 yáo', 'kiln / oven')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">窑</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=5638' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '禦 yù​', 'to defend / to resist')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">御</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=11465' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '窯 yáo', 'kiln / oven')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">窑</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=6060' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '廠 chǎng', 'factory / yard / depot / workhouse / works / cliff / slope')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">厂</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=2474' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '圖 tú', 'diagram / picture / drawing / chart')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">图</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=20699' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'zhuō​miàn​', 'desktop')" 
          onmouseout="hideToolTip()">桌面</a></div>
          <a href='/word_detail.php?id=3355' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'qīng', 'clear / distinct / complete / pure')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">清</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=8544' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Dào Guāng', 'Dao Guang / Emperor Dao Guang')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">道光</a>（1821〜1850<a href='/word_detail.php?id=438' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'nián', 'year')" 
          onmouseout="hideToolTip()">年</a>） <a href='/word_detail.php?id=737' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Běijīng', 'Beijing')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">北京</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=2887' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'shǒudū​', 'capital city')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">首都</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=3974' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '博物館 bówù​guǎn', 'Museum')" 
          onmouseout="hideToolTip()">博物馆</a>
          <div class='picture_header'>Tabletop with a Picture of the Jingdezhen Kiln Imperial Porcelain Factory</div>
          Daoguang Reign, Qing Dynasty (1821&mdash;1850),
          Capital Museum, Beijing
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        In the Yuan Dynasty, during the period 1214 to 1234, author <span class='bookTitle'>Jiang Qi</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=26486' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '蔣祈 Jiǎng​ Qí', 'Jiang Qi')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">蒋祈</a> wrote the historic book 
        <span class='bookTitle'>The Records of Ceramics</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=26054' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '陶記 Táo Jì', 'The Records of Ceramics')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">陶记</a> documenting the production of ceramics at the Jingdezhen Kiln.
        The book is of great historic value, including all the types of craftspeople involved, the sales, marketing, tax,
        and government regulation of the items.
        Later, in the Ming, Song Yingxing wrote the book called <span class='bookTitle'>Heavenly Creations</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=26055' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '天工開物 tiān Gōng Kāi Wù', 'Heavenly Creations')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">天工开物</a> on agriculture and crafts, which included a chapter on ceramics.
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class='bookTitle'>Seals</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=1850' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'kuǎn', 'section / paragraph')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">款</a> were printed on the base of porcelain works starting in the Yuan Dynasty.
        A seal from the Kangxi reign, Qing Dynasty is shown below.
        The seal reads <span class='bookTitle'>made during the reign of Emperor Kangxi, Qing Dynasty</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=15671' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Dà Qīng', 'Qing Dynasty')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">大清</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=9023' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Kāng Xī', 'Emperor Kang Xi')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">康熙</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=438' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'nián', 'year')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">年</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=658' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '製 zhì', 'to establish / to create / to make / to manufacture')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">制</a>.
        Some seals omit <span class='bookTitle'>Qing Dynasty</span> <a href='/word_detail.php?id=15671' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'Dà Qīng', 'Qing Dynasty')" 
        onmouseout='hideToolTip()'>大清</a>, consisting of the remaining four characters.
      </p>
